[[[0,[],0,"Bandwidth: Bluetooth is less suitable for transmitting large sets of data, especially BLE."]],[[0,[],0,"Costs: in comparison to network adapters, bluetooth is more affordable."]],[[0,[],0,"Range: the range of your device really depends on the bluetooth device and version that is used by the hardware and the smartphone/tablet. The environment might also impact the range. At a maximum you can reach 100 meters, but the average will be around 15 meters."]],[[0,[],0,"Power consumption: you can use BLE to save energy, but this will limit the throughput. If you are transferring small packages this might be interesting. The classic way of bluetooth communication is also less consuming than network connectivity."]]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Instead of writing the bluetooth code for every platform, you can choose to use a plugin that provides an abstraction layer so it’s possible to access BLE from shared code. At the time of writing, I find "],[0,[1],1,"Bluetooth LE Plugin for Xamarin"],[0,[],0," the best pick for the job. The plug-in is easy to implement and is continuously getting updates. If you want to use classic bluetooth you might want to look into some other plugins. in this post I will focus on "],[0,[2],1,"Bluetooth LE Plugin for Xamarin"],[0,[],0,"."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"When working with BLE, there are 3 (most important) different bluetooth abstraction layers:"]]],[3,"ul",[[[0,[],0,"Services: A "],[0,[3],1,"service"],[0,[],0," contains one or more characteristics. For example, you could have a service called "],[0,[4],1,"“Heart Rate service”"],[0,[],0," that includes characteristics such as “heart rate measurement.” Each service has it’s unique pre-defined 16-bit or 128-bit "],[0,[5],1,"UUID"],[0,[],0,"."]],[[0,[],0,"Characteristics: A "],[0,[6],1,"characteristic"],[0,[],0," is some kind of endpoint for a specific part of the service. Just like a service, the characteristic also has a "],[0,[5],1,"UUID"],[0,[],0,". Characteristics support a range of different interactions: read, write, notify, indicate, signedWrite, writableAuxilliaries, broadcast."]],[[0,[],0,"Descriptors: "],[0,[7],1,"Descriptors"],[0,[],0," are defined attributes that describe a characteristic value. For example, a descriptor might specify a human-readable description, an acceptable range for a characteristic’s value, or a unit of measure that is specific to a characteristic’s value."]]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Now, let’s dive into some code samples! To give you a taste of what the plugin has in store for you, some snippets:"]]],[1,"p",[[0,[8,8],2,"Scan for BLE devices (advertisements)"],[1,[],0,0],[0,[],0,"The Adapter class makes it possible to detect devices in the surrounding area. You can simply get an instance of the adapter and start scanning with the following code:"]]],[10,0],[1,"p",[[0,[8,8],2,"Connect to device"],[1,[],0,1],[0,[],0,"When you’ve found the device you want to connect to, you are able to initiate a connection with the device. After connecting successfully to a device you are able to get the available characteristics and start sending requests or start retrieving notifications from the device. When the bluetooth device doesn’t receive any requests for a specific period (may differ per device), it will disconnect to save battery power. After getting a device instance (with the previous sample), it’s fairly easy to setup a connection:"]]],[10,1],[1,"p",[[0,[9,9],2,"Note: a device scan is only necessary when connecting to the device for the first time. It’s also possible to initiate a connection based on the UUID of the device."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[8,8],2,"Get services, characteristics, descriptors"],[1,[],0,2],[0,[],0,"As described above, a service is the first abstraction layer. When an instance of a service is resolved, the characteristics of this specific service can be requested. The same goes for a characteristic and his descriptors. On a characteristic you can request the descriptors."]]],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"The different abstraction layers can be requested in a similar way, GetAll or GetById:"]]],[10,2],[1,"p",[[0,[8,8],2,"Send write command"],[1,[],0,3],[0,[],0,"After retrieving an instance of the characteristic you’re able to interact with it. Writing bytes for example:"]]],[10,3],[1,"p",[[0,[8,8],2,"Send read command"],[1,[],0,4],[0,[],0,"You can also request information from a characteristic:"]]],[10,4],[1,"p",[[0,[],0,"Pretty easy, right? To get you started, you can find an "],[0,[10],1,"example project"],[0,[],0," on the "],[0,[1],1,"Bluetooth LE Plugin GitHub"],[0,[],0," page. Although this seems pretty simple,  I’ve experienced some difficulties in making it rock solid. Some tips to improve your code:"]]],[3,"ul",[[[0,[],0,"Run bluetooth code on main thread."]],[[0,[],0,"Don’t scan for devices and send commands simultaneously, also don’t send multiple commands simultaneously. A characteristic can only execute one request at a time."]],[[0,[],0,"Adjust ScanMode to suit your use case."]],[[0,[],0,"Don’t store instances of characteristics or services."]]]],[1,"p",[[0,[8,8],2,"Related links:"]]],[3,"ul",[[[0,[],0,"Bluetooth LE plugin for Xamarin: "],[0,[1],1,"https://github.com/xabre/xamarin-bluetooth-le"]],[[0,[],0,"Android developer docs, BLE: "],[0,[11],1,"https://developer.android.com/guide/topics/connectivity/bluetooth-le.html"]],[[0,[],0,"Android developer docs, bluetooth: "],[0,[12],1,"https://developer.android.com/guide/topics/connectivity/bluetooth.html"]]]]]}

